\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The world energy demand has grown exponentially over the last decades.
 In 2015 the overall energy consumption was about 575 quadrillion British
 thermal units (Btu) and the most recent projections from the 2017 International
 Energy Outlook forecast a new pick of 736 quadrillion Btu in 2040 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "ieo2017"

\end_inset

.
 Panel A of figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:energy_trends"

\end_inset

 shows that world energy use rose by 56.9% from 1990 through 2015.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
For a direct comparison with the previously reported fact, one million Btu
 is roughly equivalent to 25.1996 tonne of oil equivalent (toe).
\end_layout

\end_inset

 In this framework, wind energy represents a key option for a sustainable
 future for two main reasons.
 First, wind is a clean and renewable energy source that produces virtually
 no toxic pollution or global warming emissions 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "energygov"

\end_inset

.
 Second, wind power production has very low operating and maintenance costs
 compared to traditional sources of energy, with nearly all the cost being
 related to turbines' construction and installation 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "cullen2013measuring"

\end_inset

.
 In accordance with this view, the US wind energy sector has been characterized
 by a fast expansion during the last fifteen years, growing from a cumulative
 power capacity of less than 2,500 MW in 1999 to about 85,000 MW at the
 end of 2017 (see panel B of figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:energy_trends"

\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Even if the public opinion is typically in favor of wind power 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "firestone2007public"

\end_inset

, the construction of wind farms has often to overcome the opposition of
 local communities.
 A major concern is that the visual and aural impact of wind farms might
 decrease house values in the surrounding areas.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Another concern is that the noise and vibrations generated by wind farms
 could directly harm individuals living close to the plant.
 Although the traditional medical literature finds no evidence of a negative
 relationship between wind turbines and health 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "knopper2011health"

\end_inset

, a recent study claims that psychological factors might play a role in
 reports of sleep disturbance by people living in the proximity of wind
 plants 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "jalali2016impact"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 For instance, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "slattery2012predominance"

\end_inset

 conduct surveys in several communities near wind farms in Texas and Iowa
 and find that one third of the respondents consider wind turbines an unattracti
ve feature of the landscape.
 In particular, the lowest levels of support are expressed by people living
 closest to wind farms, a phenomenon known as Not-In-My-Backyard 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "swofford2010public"

\end_inset

.
 From an international perspective, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "ladenburg2007willingness"

\end_inset

 estimate for Denmark that households are willing to pay between 46 and
 122 Euros per year for siting a future offshore wind farm further away
 from the coast.
 For Australia, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "hall2013societal"

\end_inset

 bring qualitative evidence of a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

social gap
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 between publicly stated support and individual local acceptance, partly
 explained by the trade-off between global environmental gains and local
 bearing of the costs of visual changes to a place or landscape.
 According to 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "toke2005explaining"

\end_inset

, these are among the reasons that explain why less than half of onshore
 wind farm applications in England and Wales are successful through the
 normal planning process.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The object of this paper is to analyze the impact of wind turbines presence
 on house prices.
 Using data on the location and building date of each turbine from the Federal
 Aviation Administration (FAA), and home prices from Zillow and the Federal
 Housing Finance Agency (FHFA), I am able to estimate changes in house prices
 for areas that are or are not allocated a wind farm.
 However, the presence of wind turbines in a given geographic area is clearly
 an endogenous outcome since infrastructure projects are usually targeted
 towards areas in specific economic conditions
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Usually wind farms are built in rural areas and have the indirect aim of
 boosting the local economy 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "doe2004"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 or influenced by political variables.
 I thus rely on two empirical strategies to try to isolate the causal impact
 of wind turbines on house prices.
 First, I instrument for wind turbines presence using the percentage of
 the area of a ZIP code or census tract with potential wind capacity in
 2008 greater than 30%, interacted with a dummy set to one in the years
 after the first wind turbine was installed in the US.
 Gross potential wind capacity factors are estimated for the US by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "lopez2012us"

\end_inset

 taking into account the technology available in 2008 and local wind resources.
 The 30% threshold is often used by engineers to determine the profitability
 of a site 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "LectureA"

\end_inset

.
 The hypothesis underlying this instrument is that locations having a larger
 area above the threshold are more likely to be allocated a wind farm.
 Second, I perform an event study analysis to investigate how house prices
 change in the years before and after a wind farm is constructed.
 The event is defined as the time in which an aggregate of at least ten
 wind turbines becomes operative in a certain location.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The results from my preferred instrumental variable specification show that
 each additional wind turbine installed in a given year decreases home prices
 by about 0.25%.
 This is a remarkable negative effect considering that, on average, 17 new
 turbines are installed in a ZIP code/year, conditional on non-zero construction.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The standard deviation is about 27 new turbines in the average ZIP code/year.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 On the other hand, the results of the event study are more noisy due to
 the intrinsic difficulty to identify an exact point in time in which a
 wind plant starts exerting a negative impact on house prices.
 Consequently, this approach appears to be less informative about the causal
 impact of wind turbines on home prices.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This paper mainly contributes to a recent literature that analyzes the detriment
al effects of wind turbines on house transaction prices.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "sims2008modelling"

\end_inset

 are among the first to study this topic, using a sample of 201 house transactio
ns within a mile of a wind farm in Cornwall, UK.
 The authors do not find any significant evidence of a causal effect of
 wind turbines on house prices, but this conclusion might be driven by the
 limitations of the data used.
 More recently, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "hoen2009impact"

\end_inset

 analyze the impact of 24 wind farms in the US using data on 7,500 sales
 of houses within 10 miles.
 In an improvement of this study, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "hoen2013spatial"

\end_inset

 use a differences-in-differences (DD) approach on more than 50,000 house
 transactions between 1996 and 2011 from areas within 10 miles of 67 wind
 farms in the US.
 Both of the aforementioned articles, however, are unable to uncover significant
 evidence of the impact of wind turbines on house prices.
 Focusing on Rhode Island, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "lang2014windy"

\end_inset

 use data from 3,254 transactions of houses within a mile of a wind turbine,
 finding no significant effect.
 A fair amount of other studies employing DD techniques have instead reached
 conclusions in favor of the hypothesis of a negative impact on house value.
 For the Netherlands, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "droes2014renewable"

\end_inset

 use 2.2 million transaction prices and find that the construction of a wind
 turbine lowers the price of houses within 2km by 1.4 percentage points.
 Similarly, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "sunak2016impact"

\end_inset

 find evidence of a negative impact of about 9-14% in two German cities.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "gibbons2015gone"

\end_inset

 develop a slightly more articulated digital elevation model to create a
 200m grid that shows if a turbine is visible or not from each location.
 The author uses then a DD comparing price changes in locations where a
 new turbine is built and is visible with different comparison groups, such
 as price changes in places where the new turbine is hidden by the terrain
 or became visible in the past.
 The main conclusion of the study is that visible wind turbines decrease
 house prices by 5-6% within 2km, and by less than 1% within 14km.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this paper, I contribute to this literature in two different ways.
 First, I enlarge the scope of the analysis using data on wind turbines
 in each state of the US through the end of 2017.
 Second, in the preferred specification, I address the endogeneity issue
 of the allocation of a wind turbine to a given geographic area using an
 instrumental variable approach similar to the one exploited by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "dinkelman2011effects"

\end_inset

, who instruments electrification projects in South Africa using land gradient.
 To my knowledge, this is the first attempt to use an IV approach to estimate
 the impact of wind turbines on house prices.
\end_layout

